04452nam a22005895i 9780228013808DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280138087 a10.1515/97802280138082doi  a(DE-B1597)657388  a(OCoLC)1351260344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aTR27.T67bB386 2022eb 7aPHO0100002bisacsh04a770.9713541223  aAP 99082qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/8250:7421 aBassnett, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPicturing Toronto :bPhotography and the Making of a Modern City /cSarah Bassnett. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (228 p.) :b84 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Beaverbrook Canadian Foundation Studies in Art History00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe City -- tMaking a Modern City -- tVisuality and City Planning -- tLiberal Subjects -- tInstruments of Reform -- tFraming Citizenship -- tArthur Goss and the Portraiture of Modern Subjectivity -- tConclusion -- tIllustration Credits -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1911, when Arthur Goss was hired as Toronto’s first official photographer, the city was at a critical juncture. Industry expansion and population growth produced pressing concerns about housing shortages, sanitation, and the health and welfare of citizens. Dispelling popular misconceptions, Picturing Toronto demonstrates that Goss and other photographers did not simply document the changing conditions of urban life – their photography contributed to the development of modern Toronto and shaped its inhabitants. Drawing on archival sources from the early twentieth century, Sarah Bassnett investigates how a range of groups, including the municipal government, social reformers, and the press, used photography to reconfigure the urban environment and constitute liberal subjects. Through a series of case studies, including the construction of the Bloor Viaduct, civic beautification plans, urban reform in “the Ward,” immigration and citizenship, and Goss’s portrait photography, Bassnett exposes how photographs were at the heart of debates over what the city should look like, how it should operate, and under what conditions it was appropriate for people to live. This lavishly illustrated book is the first study to treat images as vital elements that shaped Toronto’s social and political history. Interdisciplinary in its approach, Picturing Toronto displays the complex entanglements between photography and urban modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningzOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aPhotographerszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotographyxPolitical aspectszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotographyzOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801380840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228013808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228013808/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles